author: {'steamid': '76561198990797359', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 49, 'playtime_forever': 399, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 399, 'playtime_at_review': 399, 'last_played': 1710654276}
review:
It's the first time in many of years where the game advertised prior to release ended up being exactly what it said it would be.
I am both thrilled and tired because I opted to play it instead of sleep (wasn't the plan. Got sucked in)
They also seem chill with people modding it which opens up for some could be cool additions. 
For me it feels like Conan and Pokemon decided to have a baby and I like it a-lot.
It's too fleshed out on what it wants to be for me to relate it to Ark

author: {'steamid': '76561198353764912', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 4, 'playtime_forever': 2233, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 361, 'playtime_at_review': 2233, 'last_played': 1710650408}
review: Even though I am a huge Pokemon fan I still enjoy this think of this as Legends Arceus but with real time combat. I don't give a fuck about the who plagiarism bullshit I enjoy this game for what it is, if you are new to survival games I would say this is good for beginners even if you are a Pokemon fan like me, I notice some similarities like some of the Pals do look similar to Pokemon. Like my favorite Pal in this game is definitely Katress because she reminds me of my favorite Pokemon, which is Espeon, but imagine Espeon getting a fusion with Mismagius you get yourself Katress. Also free Pal Alliance is basically Team Plasma in this game. All in all I enjoy this game despite what the Pokemon company says. Also even though I am a big fan of Pokemon and I also love Nintendo the developers of this game at least care. TAKE NOTES NINTENDO!!!

review: This is a game that is a mash up of great mechanics that you see in a variety of different games all in one. Its one of those things that if seen individually would seem like a rip off but in unison it comes out original. author: {'steamid': '76561198049088202', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 5685, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 55, 'playtime_at_review': 5685, 'last_played': 1710048413}
review: Ark style building/survival with Pokemon style capturing mechanics. If you liked Ark and wanted a change of pace Id strongly recommend PalWorld. Be warned that late game gets slow progression wise, past level 35 or so there is a significant xp wall youll hit and progression almost stops. Playing solo I turned up the xp multiplier and continued to enjoy the game thru level 50. My primary gripe with the game is simply how tedious it is to earn tech points to unlock all of the recipes for saddles and armor. It is a little sad having captured every Pal and not being able to use/ride a lot of them without sinking a few hours into getting enough tech manuals to unlock the recipe. Overall I do plan to come back to the game when more content is added because the game itself is a fun time to be had.

author: {'steamid': '76561198017893260', 'num_games_owned': 144, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 5612, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 3471, 'playtime_at_review': 5612, 'last_played': 1710632317}
review:
I'm level 45, I think. I have my Assault Rifle and can make the ammo. This game gets kind of deep. I actually felt bad for beating Zoe (think Kuroko Shirai from Railgun; all grown up) and Grizzbolt after reading her story.

The draw distance blows my mind. Oh, you see something? You can go there... Other than that huge tree (normally...).

I wonder how this game looks on better GPUs. I'm running a laptop RTX 3060 6GB. So far so good, but I find my power brick gets hot and the system throttles accordingly. Dellienware power bricks don't have the best reputation for sustained output. The power brick in question is a 240W model. No GaN transistor tech. Palworld is doing here what The Orange Box did for snuffing X360 GPUs before the warranty ran out; finding flaws that should never have existed and making them obvious.

This game has so much potential.

author: {'steamid': '76561198057851820', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 3536, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 16, 'playtime_at_review': 3536, 'last_played': 1709706748}
review:
If there is a single original thought in this game, I've yet to find it.

Unfortunately, that's kind of Palworld's whole selling point. People look at it on a surface level and go "hey, something different in the battlepets genre" and handwave a lot of the blatant copyright infringement because its apparent biggest contender is Nintendo, and it's easy to hate on a large company that's let down its fanbase over and over. I don't exactly blame people for that, either--I'm fed up with the same slop Nintendo keeps shilling out that it calls Pokemon that ignores a lot of criticisms and actual wants of its playerbase. But this isn't good enough to fill that void.

The gameplay: One of the better points of Palworld. The combat working in tandem with Pals for combinations such as having a monkey go off with an assault rifle, or a chipmunk on your head going nuts with a submachine gun has so much potential. Things like having to craft the specific items to use certain Pals as mounts, or for them to just be out by your side regardless of it being your current "summoned" one, is a very nice touch. This stuff has promise. From a design perspective, if Palworld leaned far more into a comedic aspect with these gameplay elements, you'd have a solid, distinctive game with this. It doesn't though--it leans into a more generic fantasy adventure and that affects the gameplay as much as the appearance, but we'll get to that later. For now, while I liked these aspects of the Pals, it loses its luster very, very quickly. Combat is challenging up to a certain point, and while it can be funny at first to get roflstomped by the mammoth in the starter area if you accidentally poke it even after you cross the challenge threshold, after you pass that threshold, combat gets pretty stale. Attack something, dodge its attacks, rotate your Pals, throw a sphere, and flee--these are your combat options. Typing doesn't really matter, strategic placement/movement only matters if its the only way to block something, and if you can't kill something just by kiting in circles and shooting it long enough alongside your Pals, then either you need better gear or more levels and you're good. That's it. There's nothing else to the combat. No using a fire-type to melt through barriers and walls to solve puzzles, no using an electric-type to temporarily power stage elements to escape or trap a boss, no using water- or ice-types to flood or freeze certain sections to reach otherwise inaccessible areas. Not that the latter is needed, since the player can climb LITERALLY ANYTHING as we are apparently part goat--not necessarily a critique, mind, though I do find it funny. I do like the implementation of the glider and the ability to drop and restart it while falling a considerable distance. Travelling on foot is often easier and better than trying to ride around on any unlocked mounts, which kind of defeats the purpose of mounts in the first place. This game also sports crafting which is okay, I guess, aside from the weird jank of placing walls around your base. You can smelt, make weapons, cook, refine wood and stone, log, mine, and build, and Pals can help you with all these tasks which is nice. You can set up a bunch of stations that the Pals will work on if left to their own devices, or you can assign them specific stations and they'll focus only on that station, which is handy. There's nothing particularly noteworthy about the crafting, except that you can access everything in your base without it needing to be on your person, which is NICE. Wish more games did that. 5/10 overall--the foundations are there, but it's dead boring before too long. Some of the balancing leaves something to be desired, too.

The world: Snooze. Dull. Boring. Forgettable. I don't know if it's because the gameplay isn't engaging enough or what, but the map for the most part is just...forgettable. The one exception is one very tall, very sharp ridge reminiscent of Pride Rock, but aside from that, nothing really excites me about the world. There's no interesting features, no memorable landmarks, nothing that makes anything stick. It feels like the map was solely created as a place for the Pals with no character of its own, and things just kind of....happen. How have Pals with all their weird powers shaped and twisted the landscape? What about bizarre and alien terrains unique to the world that are the only environments certain Pals live in? How has human colonization disrupted the ecosystem? What about the ancient tech and its impact? There's hints about these things, but nothing that actually makes them feel solid and impactful, and the lore entries just aren't enough to fill the gaps. It's pretty to look at, but not much else. The fact that it's the exact same map every time you start up a game, and that starting points aren't even randomized, just makes it feel even more dull and safe. 4/10 for just being pretty decor.

The Pals/design: Oh boy. Where do I start. Incineram is literally just Zoroark with horns and splashes of white. Felbat is LITERALLY DARKRAI. YOU CANNOT TELL ME THAT IS NOT COPYRIGHT INFRINGEMENT, from the color scheme to the shape of its mane and everything! Chikipi and Lamball are just cartoonish chickens and sheep with nothing unique about them, Pengullet is basically Piplup but dark blue, though I guess an argument could be made for a bland, stylized penguin, which still leaves it with nothing distinctive. Lovander and the grass monkey thing are just memes, basically. Every. Single. Pal. is like this. Even if there isn't any copyright infringement/plagiarism--which there is in goddamn spades--there's nothing distinctive, nothing unique about Palworld's design that is truly its own. Nothing stands out. Nothing is unique. It's constantly compared to Legend of Zelda, Pokemon, and Monster Hunter, and this is NOT a good thing. There's drawing INSPIRATION from these games, making similar elements, and making a game distinctly your own (like how Baldur's Gate is Baldur's Gate even if it's D&D), and then there's just mashing together a bunch of things you like directly from other games. Palworld does the latter. It's a mishmash of other elements from other games it really liked, and while that in and of itself isn't necessarily a bad thing, you have to do something to make it your OWN, to make your game stand out as UNIQUE. Palworld doesn't have that at all, and without something to truly distinguish it from Pokemon/LoZ/Monster Hunter, it is inevitably doomed to fail. -2/10 for lack of originality where it counts. Additional points off for blatant plagiarism (and for stealing from small time creators at that!).

2.2/10. I never would've played this game if a friend hadn't gifted it to me, to be honest. Not that I'm upset that they did, not in the least--this is just something I never would've acquired otherwise. It's not worth $30 for something that will be entertaining for all of a month before it sits in your Steam library, utterly forgotten for the rest of time. That, and I can't condone a game that commits blatant theft (look up Mega-Delphox by Pyroaura98 for one example). Regardless of your thoughts on Nintendo and Pokemon, supporting this game isn't "sticking it to the man." That said, buy it if you want, I just hope my review has been helpful in some way.

author: {'steamid': '76561198438427438', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 950, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 950, 'playtime_at_review': 813, 'last_played': 1710635411}
review:
Palworld: Where Whimsy Meets Chaos in the Strangest of Ways!

Step into a world where the line between reality and absurdity blurs, where whimsical creatures roam free, and where madness reigns supreme. Welcome to Palworld, the latest creation from the brilliantly bizarre minds at Pocketpair.

From the moment you boot up this surreal experience, you'll find yourself in a whirlwind of hilarity and chaos. Picture this: you're merrily frolicking through fields with your trusty companions, only to realise that those companions are not your typical pets â€“ they're sentient beings that can wield firearms, build structures, and even engage in combat alongside you. Yes, you heard that right. Palworld takes the concept of "pet simulation" to a whole new level, blurring the lines between animal companion and fully-fledged sidekick.

But that's just the tip of the iceberg. As you delve deeper into the world of Palworld, you'll encounter a myriad of absurdities that will leave you scratching your head in disbelief. Need to defend your homestead from marauding bandits? Why not strap a rocket launcher to your llama and let it rain explosive justice upon your foes? Want to build a fortress to keep your pals safe? Just gather some resources and watch as your cuddly critters construct a towering stronghold with uncanny efficiency.

The sheer absurdity of Palworld is both its greatest strength and its most endearing quality. Every moment spent in this wacky wonderland is filled with laughter, surprise, and a healthy dose of "what on earth am I playing?" The game doesn't take itself too seriously, and neither should you. Embrace the madness, revel in the chaos, and let yourself be whisked away on a journey unlike any other.

Of course, Palworld isn't without its quirks. The controls can be a bit wonky at times, and the AI of your pal companions can be... let's just say unpredictable. But these minor flaws only add to the game's charm, serving as a reminder that perfection is overrated when you're having this much fun.

In conclusion, Palworld is a delightful romp through a world where the absurd reigns supreme. With its whimsical creatures, outlandish game play mechanics, and unabashedly chaotic energy, it's a game that defies explanation and demands to be experienced firsthand. So grab your favourite pal, saddle up your llama, and prepare for an adventure unlike any other. Just don't forget to pack your sense of humour â€“ you're going to need it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198088381842', 'num_games_owned': 335, 'num_reviews': 49, 'playtime_forever': 1042, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 419, 'playtime_at_review': 1042, 'last_played': 1709891681}
review:
The opening area is great and shows what this game could potentially be really well. Unfortunately after a bit the grind really kicks in and the Early Access status makes itself known. This game could be great, but right now it's good. 

The art, the core gameplay loop and the base building all feel pretty strong at this stage. I was afraid the game would also lack its own identity and be too derivative, but it actually ends up being so much more than the pieces it's taking from. The survival elements and progression at first seem like typical survival game stuff, but the pals are such a key factor in all of it that it really changes a lot of that typical formula into something pleasantly unfamiliar. The pals on the surface may seem just like Pokemon, but they function significantly differently in here and are a fair bit more autonomous. Overall the positives are very strong on this game and a great core structure to build upon. 

Now for the negatives. 

First of all, I'm not a particularly big fan of the devs leaving their previous game sitting in early access. Craftopia was a game I tried on Game Pass and it felt like a giant mish-mash of different elements put into one game that never really came together to create something interesting. The game still currently sits unfinished in early access, and while Palworld is ultimately a lot more successful, it has the potential of going the same route as Craftopia. 

The AI in this game is a complete joke. Whether enemy or ally, pal or human, the AI is absolutely pathetic. Pals often get stuck around your base doing basic tasks and then can't get to their bed or grab food. Pals sometimes glitch out on terrain as well. But worse than this are the goons you will find in the world. In half of the fights I've had with them they've just kind of stood there and don't really do anything. The targeting is also really weird. Sometimes you send your pal out to wreak havoc and they'll just try (and often fail) to shoot you 50m away, despite the fact that a giant wolf is tearing their friends apart right next to them. 

I think another thing that suffers is the world itself. The world is big, empty and often pointless. So many open spaces could do with more variety. More variety of pals, more variety of activities, of loot etc. When you do happen across something different, it feels solid, but most of the time exploring this giant map is just looking for something to do or harvesting resources. The world could be fleshed out more, as it seems the further you venture outwards, the less dense it is. 

Lastly, I think the progression needs some tuning. It became a real grind to level up, and the rewards feel less and less important the higher you get. Unlocking new tech becomes more expensive and sometimes less valuable than what you had. Upgrading your base exponentially increases in difficulty. The little incremental stat increases could also honestly do with some serious changes. A proper skill tree that opens up interesting builds or tying more of these stats to your equipment/pals would be much better than getting a flat increase to a bunch of basic numbers. 

Overall, these negatives might sound harsh, but the positives are just as strong. I just hope that some of these issues are addressed going forward in future updates. The devs have clearly found a lot of success, so I'm curious as to what that would mean for the product as it nears completion.

review:
UW Developers!
After your patch v0.1.4.1 (which simply ruined the game), the behavior of the fireballs on the base became inadequate!!!

(Working regime is the most gentle!!!)
1. Constantly hungry. They run to eat every 1.5 minutes (feeders are full! Any kind of food.)
2. PADS are not fixed at the place of work.
3. They constantly leave their place of work and get stuck in an empty place on the border of the base! We have to build walls BEFORE the perimeter of the border.
4. They don't sleep in beds. They lie directly on the ground, on the street.
5. They constantly get stuck in textures. That is, they donâ€™t walk on stairs or paths, but try to go through walls and containers.
6. In the buildings, the second floor has become completely non-functional. They donâ€™t go there to eat, sleep or work.
7. When the HUNGRY fell, he, they, follow you on your heels, (although the feeders are in front of your nose and filled with food) until you feed them by hand.

I donâ€™t know how the behavior of the fells has changed outside the borders of the base, because I donâ€™t have time to go hunting, but I donâ€™t think that they have become more adequate. And if so, then I feel sorry for dragging them to the base, because they will also become infected with madness!
In general - I am indignant!

At the moment I can recommend the game for review.
The impression is more positive than negative. But itâ€™s not yet possible to play it fully! There are a lot of bugs.
Dislike.
I'll correct it with a like if they work on the mistakes.

review:
I have had a lot of fun on this game.
- Pros: The scenery is beautiful and it gives you the option to choose the difficulty of the game. Your base can be almost completely auto-sustainable and is fun to capture pals. You can choose from surviving to, exploring, to capture all the pals, to breed pals, to plan a beautiful base, to do towers, to do trial, or dungeons. There is a lot of choices of things the game provide. You have the liberty to choose how to play your own game. If you want to play solo or online.
-Cons: Needs a little bit of storyline.
Even, though, I love this game and I recommend it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198122875356', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 7, 'playtime_forever': 3557, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 361, 'playtime_at_review': 3557, 'last_played': 1710586804}
review:
A third person action game where you catch different creatures to do your bidding [i](even humans can be captured)[/i]. These creatures [i](pals)[/i] can be used as slaves to craft and gather items in your base. The only thing you need to provide them is food and somewhere to sleep and bathe. Doing that will keep the pals sanity up. If sanity drops too low, the work speed drops dramatically. However you can of course always execute or sell the pal if they are not a good worker. The game doesn't really have a story but there are a few tower bosses to beat.

[h1]Gameplay[/h1]
[b]Pals[/b]: There are 100+ different pals in the game. It is possible to craft a saddle and ride most of them. Pals have different stats and skills, for example some can chop down wood and some plant seeds. Some pals are very clearly intended to be used in base and some in a party as a mode of transport or attacker [i](or both)[/i]. Pals can be acquired either by catching them with pal-spheres or by hatching them from an egg. It is also possible to acquire a pal from an enemy camp or from a merchant. Sometimes catching pals feels a bit awkward since the pal can randomly block the sphere or the sphere just goes directly through the pal. Finally when you manage to successfully hit the pal with a sphere the pal attacks you from inside the sphere.

[b]Movement[/b]: The character moves smoothly but the stamina runs out really fast. Running around is very slow so naturally most of the moving around is done via riding a pal. It is possible to craft a grappling gun to help you move on cliffsides. Grappling gun is also very useful when moving large amounts of items [i](there is a weight limit but it can be bypassed with a grappling gun)[/i]. Glider can also be crafted and used to glide over ravines or to prevent fall damage when jumping from a cliff [i](some pals can be used as a glider as well)[/i]. Sometimes the pal pathfinding does weird things, for example when the pal is on water. Luckily a lot of improvements have been made to pathfinding since launch [i](and most likely more will be made)[/i].

[b]World[/b]: The world is absolutely huge and luckily there are fast travel points. The world seems to be well though out. It is divided into regions were the flora and the difficulty level varies. There are for example a volcano, ice mountains and a desert. There are occasionally some weird lighting glitches [i](especially in caves)[/i]. Now for the big issue at hand, optimization. There are areas where the performance drops dramatically. Let's say the game runs most of the time 60 fps then suddenly the framerate drops to ~10 fps. It is pretty much game over at that point if powerful enemies attack.

[b]Building[/b]: Building seems to be working well in flat areas. However building on a cliffside for example can be very challenging because walls cannot be placed if they overlap with a terrain even a little. There are of course little tricks to get around the issue. Also a lot of pretty important features are missing such as stackable foundations, fences and pillars just to name a few. However the problem with building is that you are allowed to have the maximum of three bases. This is very frustrating in singleplayer since the map has so many awesome building locations. Hopefully in the future there will be an option to change the maximum base limit in the world settings or something.

[b]Crime[/b]: Despite slavery there are laws in the world and breaking them will result in a wanted-level. Attacking a non-enemy npc or trespassing on a wildlife sanctuary is considered a crime. If the authorities [i](PIDF)[/i] see that you have committed a crime, they will hunt you down to the ends of the world [i](literally)[/i]. The only way escape the PIDF is to die or destroy the pursuing forces.

[h1]Would I recommend this game?[/h1]
- Yes it is absolutely fun, a lot of optimization needed though.
- World settings can be customized and there are external mods available.
- Achievements are not too hard to complete.

author: {'steamid': '76561198092531775', 'num_games_owned': 112, 'num_reviews': 58, 'playtime_forever': 385, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 385, 'last_played': 1707404162}
review: I have played this game and enjoyed exploring the world and taming the creatures. I have unlocked all possible blue prints,explored the whole map and I have to say that after 6 hours of game play, that I started to get bored and the game becomes repetitive. The Boss dungeons are not scaled to your player levels and can not be completed even after unlocking the best animals.I do not believe you should have your first quest boss dungeon be as difficult as it is, when you are learning the mechanics and to completely get pummeled in seconds. this whole system needs a work around in my opinion. I Do not recommend buying this game at its current state of game play, as it needs serious content and bug fix updates. I had really high hopes for this game and I am so disappointed at the limited content available to play. You can't even sit or use the furniture you unlock for your house and when placing your base pylon you get such little space to build on that it is cringe worthy. They basically give you a little circle and that is what they make u cramp all these huge quest based objective furniture. The animals are cute, but that is the only good feature at this moment. I understand it is early access but for the amount of time they took to build this game, I would have expected so much more for the price point. I would wait to get this game on sale if you are considering purchasing it. I am not saying it is a bad game, but that there are too many frustrating qualities at this point of early access for me to personally recommend it to any of my friends.

review:
Pokemon meets Ark Survival with a bit of Fortnite thrown in. Really good in its current state, definitely worth the price, will be even better once updates to building and general content drop. 

Building is frustrating atm, restrictions on part placement are too fussy and not very many building pieces available, but plenty of furniture. 

Map is amazing, huge, so much to explore. But far too few POI's atm. does need more content. 

Still more than enough to keep busy for now. Really enjoying this game alot and looking forward to updates and full game release!

author: {'steamid': '76561197998490326', 'num_games_owned': 2646, 'num_reviews': 53, 'playtime_forever': 1872, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 1872, 'playtime_at_review': 1847, 'last_played': 1710601478}
review:
TL;DR It's a mixed bag right now, especially with bugs. Wait until it's more polished.

There are some good ideas, and parts of the game can be fun.
But there is still a lot that needs more work, and there are a lot of bugs as well, from mildly annoying to incredibly frustrating. In no particular order, and only a selection of issues i've encountered:

- AI Pathfinding is awful, pals and NPCs get stuck constantly
- Assigning pals to specific tasks is simply not doable right now, which makes managing a base very frustrating. on paper you can automate a lot of things, in reality you have to do a lot of things yourself, or constantly micromanage pals. It feels like i'm just doing chores instead of doing fun things i want to do a lot of the time.
- auto aim "feature" that actually makes attacks miss a lot, and can't find a setting to disable it
- Bad UI - some screens take several Esc presses to get out of, i often have to click through various menus to get to the information i want (why is info on habitats of pals not accessible from the context detailed info screen, or at least a link to the paldex? There is no search function in the paldex either, so if you want to look up info on a pal....you have to scroll through the whole list to find it). In short, it's very frustrating how much work it is to make the game do what you want, or get the information you want and it feels like you have to fight the UI
- Bugs: Crashing, performance drops, getting stuck in terrain - it's pretty buggy, and not in a charming way
- Mod support, which is good - at the same time, mods often don't work or cause crashes, and error messages are not very helpful
- Raids on your bases can be ridiculously overpowered - got around level 30 enemies attacking while at level 15 or so
- riding pals sounds great in theory, in practice you shouldn't ride pals in combat because attacks will also hit you, and you will die very fast. It's just sad that riding pals is disencouraged in that way. And related...
- armor breaks extremely quickly, and is expensive to repair
- Sensory overloading - if you're sensitive to flashing and the like, expect a rough time. Mining animations are very flashy, mining at night in particular is awful with very dark background and then huge bright flashes. Personally i avoid mining at night altogether, there are no settings to disable this either; could use more thought on accessibility.

I could go on. It is playable. And yes it can be fun. But it definitely feels like early access and is often frustrating, and you'll do yourself a favour by waiting some more time so the devs can hopefully polish the game up and make it a smoother experience. The foundation for a good game is absolutely there, and i hope it'll get there in a year or two.

review: En general es entretenido, me he pasado algunas buenas risas con amigos y he tenido la oportunidad de probar las versiones de Microsoft Store y Steam, sin duda la de Steam tiene un mejor rendimiento. Aun asÃ­, no puedo creer que una 2060 Super vaya a menos de 60fps con grÃ¡ficos en medio. Falta muchisima optimizaciÃ³n al juego, y al principio va bien. Luego de que tienes una base con muchos Pals y objetos construidos el rendimiento empieza a bajar y la memoria RAM empieza a ser insuficiente (el juego me ha llegado a ocupar 28 de las 32GB que tengo en mi equipo). En verdad es una burla. Entiendo que es un early access pero con todo el hype que hubo del juego ya debieron encontrar talento suficiente en la desarrolladora para que pudiera ayudar a mejorar esas cuestiones tÃ©cnicas. author: {'steamid': '76561198150858660', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 4476, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 139, 'playtime_at_review': 4412, 'last_played': 1710566513}
review:
Hooked on this game, it fills a void in my heart Nintendo has never been able to fill.
For an indie game it is very fleshed out with a lot of thought put into it, if you can look at it from a realistic stand point its a game preview, so all the small bugs aside, I'd say game is released in a better state than most AAA titles are these days.

There is enough here to keep you going for many hours and or multiple play through's if you ramp up the difficulty and really take your time exploring each area.

Very excited to see what the final product looks like.

author: {'steamid': '76561198059772690', 'num_games_owned': 122, 'num_reviews': 34, 'playtime_forever': 1769, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1769, 'last_played': 1708317148}
review:
It's a good game. Ignore what people say, if you like survival stuff and Pokemon it's worth a try.
If you're still worried, give it some time. The early access is real with this one but devs do seem to like the game.

About the copying pokemon and game is just ark stuffs, this is a normal thing in the industry called a "remix." Think like music, it's literally the same concept. It is a lot like Ark, and some of the pals look a lot like other pokemon. You're not meant to be here for the originality of this, target audience is people who enjoy both of that stuff.

(mad props to PirateSoftware for expanding my brain about that remix term, check his streams/vods/games cool guy knows a lot about the game industry, mans survived working at blizzard lol)

author: {'steamid': '76561198043256632', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 5400, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 76, 'playtime_at_review': 5400, 'last_played': 1709458380}
review:
Palworld really is an incredible game, especially considering that it is not a AAA title. From Day One, I fell in love with the game. While it still has a ways to go, being in Early Access still, it really has set a new standard that I genuinely hope terrifies all of these AAA devs. I only wish that I had more time to play since my normal group has moved on to a different game, and I only get a few hours every night to actually play games. All in all, these game is absolutely worth the money, and if you are genuinely interested I could not more highly recommend it.
Side note: Don't listen to the knuckle-draggers that try to tell you that it's just a PokÃ©mon rip-off. They're just mad that Palworld has delivered more quality than PokÃ©mon has in several games, and they're only just getting started.

Fantastic game already, even in early access. This is the perfect marriage of ARK and Legends: Arceus. All of the joy of building/surviving from ARK with none of the tedium, and all of the fun of Legends: Arceus without having to play on one of the most underpowered hardware systems in modern gaming history.

I cannot wait to keep playing this as it gets better and better. It's already so fun.

review:
Good game. I enjoy playing it with friends and solo. 

I wish that the spheres you throw that don't make contact with the pal you are trying to collect could be picked up and reused. 

The only bug/issue I ran into is that sometimes pals will glitch into the mountain or the ground. So be careful when attacking pals close to mountains the attack may push them into the wall/mountain.

author: {'steamid': '76561198112935071', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 4, 'playtime_forever': 2425, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 2425, 'playtime_at_review': 1983, 'last_played': 1710629149}
review: i found this game on the Xbox One S console and it was kicking me out and freezing alot. I just figured this was an issue with some server in the background and it was pretty widely known on the internet already. However, i found one person from xbox dev. team giving and actual honest answer that it wasn't the game or servers. it was in fact an issue where the older console doesn' t have enough memory or updated hardware essentially to run the game. Im not sure why they continued to put that game to that specific platform but not my call. when i saw this and realized there was most likely a PC game and found it on steam here it was a game changer. This is game runs flawlessly on PC. I have never been dropped or frozen since. I love this game. its a perfect mix between the iconic "gotta catch em all" feel and open world exploration that gamers like myself love. im having a blast and i have a couple bases with a good pal team. i enjoy sitting back relaxing and finding a new area i haven't seen while exploring. I will recommend this to others on PC from now on and i look forward to the many updates and fun content! Thanks for all the hard work and an awesome game! (to all those whose are working still/worked on the game).
